(5bn (EV) minus 781m) x 69% = 2.9bn. I.e. the formula is EV minus debt plus cash (or similar) x share of the company = the purchase price.

In reality it is a little more complicated, because the 781m figure does not include the club’s agreed transfer fees to be paid over time (over 200m), that could also be called debt, in which case the total debt figure should be closer to a billion. At the same time — we also have sold a ton of commercial rights to be paid for over time. How to view this in a M&A transaction is not written in stone and ultimately it’s a question for an accountant not a lawyer like myself — but I think there are reasons to assume that either (a) the “transfer debt” won’t be seen as genuine debt or (b) it is, but we also have significant value tied up in sold but not yet paid commercial rights, so the total net sum to be removed from the EV will be closer to 781m anyway.
